{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f1afaf6-3793-4b39-8485-a3c5a11acd42","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .NET crash dump! While I don't have a specialized skill for **analyzing** dumps (the `dump-collect` skill is for *collecting* them), here's how to proceed:\n\n### Recommended Tools\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform)\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n   ```\n   Useful commands inside the analyzer:\n   - `clrstack` — managed call stack\n   - `pe` — print last exception\n   - `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n   - `threads` — list all threads\n\n2. **WinDbg** (Windows, most powerful)\n   - Load the dump, then `.loadby sos clr` (Framework) or `.loadby sos coreclr` (modern .NET)\n   - `!pe` — print exception\n   - `!clrstack` — managed stack\n   - `!analyze -v` — automated crash analysis\n\n3. **Visual Studio** (Windows)\n   - File → Open → File → select `.dmp`\n   - Click \"Debug with Managed Only\"\n\n### Quick Start\n\nIf you can share the dump or run commands on your machine, I'd suggest starting with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nThen run `pe` (print exception) to see the crash reason, followed by `clrstack` for the call stack.\n\nWould you like me to walk you through any of these steps, or do you have the dump file accessible in this environment?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"621f5d4b-20c8-4ec1-986d-eeb945463d28","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application and wants help analyzing it. Let me help them with this. I should check if there are any relevant skills available - looking at the available skills, I see \"dump-collect\" but that's for collecting dumps, not analyzing them. Let me provide guidance on analyzing .NET crash dumps.\n\nLet me give them practical advice on how to analyze the dump file.","outputTokens":478,"requestId":"CB02:20BD61:735A8C:84904C:6A052B6B"},"id":